column17: One of the top prospects in Connecticut...............Sophomore starter at QB on a 6-2 NEPSAC A team (QB/WR/FS) and he was 131 of 230 passing for 1,905 yards (.570), 15 TDs and 7 INTs, and he had 115 carries for 448 yards (3.9ypc) and 6 TDs..................He transferred from Bridgeport Harding to Avon Old farms for the 2016 season and re-classified from '18 to '19 class...............Final soph passing stats:  126/208-60.6%-2,315 yards-30 TDs-5 INTs................As a sophomore QB on a 9-0 Class L team he had completed 110 of 181 passes for 2,087 yards (.608), 28 TDs and just 3 INTs, and had 32 carries for 282 yards (8.8ypc) and 2 TDs................As a freshman starter at QB on a 5-6 Class L team he completed 187 of 312 passes for 2,540 yards (.599), 20 TDs and 12 INTs, and had 26 caries for 265 yards (10.2ypc) and 1 TD, and 26 punts for a 29.7 avg............Dual-threat QB.  Great frame, must fill out and get a lot stronger but runs well, is athletic and has a live arm, throwing dimes as a freshman.  Power Five prospect..........“He’s probably one of the best quarterbacks that we’ve seen in a long time across the state,” Harding coach Eddie Santiago said in August 2015. “I’m not being light with that. I truly believe that. I don’t know too many freshman that did what he did. We lost our starting center, we lost our left tackle last year. With the things that happened to our program last year, and the things he was able to overcome, he’s a special, special kid.”  “Anytime I get a call from a coach,” Santiago said, “the first thing they say is, ‘Hey, you’ve got a hell of a quarterback out there in Bridgeport.’ They’re already inquiring about him. We don’t have any direct offers, but everybody’s recruiting him. … I’m very excited for him. The offers will come.”...........Camped at Miami in July 2017...............Invited to January 2017 U.S. Army Combine in San Antonio............Registered to participate in the January 2016 U.S. Army National Combine in San Antonio..........He shined in August 2015 at the invite-only New York vs. New England All-Star Challenge at Stamford High, coming off the scout team to throw a pair of touchdowns. What he’s lacking right now is game experience at the varsity level, and all you can do is put him out there and let him get it. We know he’s going to make mistakes, and there will be some growing pains no doubt, but I’m telling you don’t sleep on Wiley Cain. Harding coach Sam Griner thinks he may have the best running back in Mecklenburg County history.  "Some people are just made for the sport," Griner said of Crouch in November 2015.  “You look at him and think, ‘This kid has it all and he doesn’t have to work hard,’ ” Greiner said. “But he wants to be great. I coached (South Carolina linebacker) Larenz Bryant when he was at Vance and he was special. Quavaris is stronger than Larenz as a freshman."..........“He’s amazing,” Ardrey Kell coach Joe Evans said in November 2015. “He reversed field on us on one run and we had him in the backfield for a 5-yard loss. He had a great game against us and we stacked the box against him. He’s going to be special.”............Very impressive at April 2016 Charlotte Rivals Camp..............LSU fan..............Visited Clemson for November 2015 Wake Forest game...............As of November 2015 he had heard from UNCC (offer), Clemson and North Carolina............Visited Alabama and Michigan in July 2017

P5 talent..........Perhaps Wilmore’s defining moment as a sophomore came in the CIF Southern Section Division 6 quarterfinals when he knew he had to keep up with Summit senior five-star running back Stephen Carr. column17: One of the top prospects in Washington.................Sophomore starter at OT on a 1-0 3A team..............'Freshman starter at OT on a 3-7 4A team and he had 3 tackles (T/DT)...............Remarkable story.  At age 10, Bailey Elder was diagnosed with autism.  Few of Elder’s teammates know about his diagnosis. Because it’s a spectrum disorder, some people, like Elder, are mildly impaired, while others are more severely disabled, according to the National Institute of Mental Health. Despite his autism he is an outstanding student and took AP calculus as a frehsman and was attending math classes at  SAMI -Science and Math Institute in Tacoma and as of December 2015 already had over 1/2 of the credits he needed to graduate from High School.  Elder plays football for Stadium, but attends Tacoma’s Science and Math Institute (SAMI). He also has Dysgraphia, which makes it difficult for him to write coherently. He needs a scribe to assist him with assignments.  On the field he has great size, bends well, has great hips and is very aggressive.
